Orchestrator is the entry point of this engine. User usually creates the prompt in the format
{Textual query, List of files}. And this list of files can be present in different project repos.
Within in each project repo, few of them can be code files, where as others can be non-code files.

Pre-processing - 
Before sending the prompt the model, we intercept and try to accomplish the task in smaller footprint of tokens
For a new model request, a new sessionMapObject is created with it's unique session id.
Then we loop through each project id -
Each one of the code file under it is passed through the codeSquasher logic in the parser module.
Once we have the list of compressed code files, we then generate the prompt, quoting/passing these compressed files.

Model request-response -
Before making the request to the model, ensure it follows the format mentioned in the file prompt_format.txt
The model reads the newly created squashed prompt and answers back the response in the desired format.

Post-processing - 
The above model response will have both the textual response and the list of modified code files <cf1,cf2,...> in the compressed space.
Each one of these are of compressed format and we need to send it to the responseBuilder
In the above list, few of them might have been compressed and need to be decompressed, if so we need to send it to the responseBuilder
to get the corresponding file in the decompressed space.
If any of the file has been newly created, then just leave it as is.
And for the textual part, we pass it along with required params to the relaxTextual in the decompressor module and get the textual response.
Essentially, this responseBuilder module recreates both the textual response and the code blocks in the original code space with modifications.
And that's how we send back the response to the user providing both the textual response and the code modifications with all the diffs suggested by the model.